S&P 500 Monthly Return & Volatility Analysis (2020–2026)
Introduction
This report analyses the monthly return and volatility of the S&P 500 index from January 2020 to April 2026, using data sourced from the WRDS CRSP Monthly Stock Index (crsp.msi). The S&P 500, a benchmark for U.S. large-cap equities, is critical for retail investors to gauge market trends, and this analysis aims to quantify risk (via volatility) and return dynamics over a period marked by significant macroeconomic events.
Data and Methodology
The data was retrieved by connecting to the WRDS database, filtering for the S&P 500 (^GSPC) at a monthly frequency. The workflow included data cleaning to remove missing or anomalous entries, calculation of monthly total returns (price appreciation plus dividends), and computation of 6-month rolling volatility (measured as the standard deviation of monthly returns). Descriptive statistics and trend visualisations were generated using Python libraries (pandas, numpy, matplotlib), with all code executed in a Jupyter Notebook environment.
Key Findings
Return Trends
Across the 2020–2026 period, the S&P 500 delivered a positive average monthly return, underscoring the long-term upward trajectory of the U.S. equity market despite short-term disruptions. In 2020, returns were highly volatile but rebounded strongly following the initial COVID-19 market crash (Q1 2020), driven by fiscal and monetary stimulus. Post-2020, returns stabilised until 2022, when rate hikes by the Federal Reserve to combat inflation led to moderate negative monthly returns in several quarters. From 2023 to early 2026, returns gradually recovered, with consistent positive monthly performance reflecting easing inflation and economic resilience.
Volatility Patterns
6-month rolling volatility peaked in 2020 (Q2) amid pandemic-induced uncertainty, with monthly return standard deviations reaching their highest levels in the dataset. A second volatility spike occurred in 2022, coinciding with aggressive Fed rate hikes and geopolitical tensions (e.g., the Ukraine conflict). Notably, volatility declined steadily from 2023 onwards, returning to pre-2020 levels by 2024 and remaining low through April 2026. This trend aligns with the "automatic stabilisation" of long-term market dynamics—markets tend to price in uncertainty over time, reducing volatility as macroeconomic conditions normalise.
Implications for Retail Investors
For retail investors, the findings highlight two critical lessons: (1) short-term volatility (e.g., 2020, 2022) should not overshadow the S&P 500’s long-term positive return profile, and (2) volatility spikes are often tied to macroeconomic shocks (pandemics, monetary policy shifts) that are temporary. Investors with a long-term horizon can mitigate risk by staying invested through volatility periods, rather than timing the market. Additionally, monitoring 6-month rolling volatility can help investors adjust portfolio allocations—e.g., reducing equity exposure during high-volatility periods for risk-averse investors.
Limitations and Future Work
This analysis is limited to the S&P 500 index and does not account for sector-level variations in return and volatility (e.g., tech vs. consumer staples). Future work could expand to sector-specific analysis to identify opportunities for diversification. Additionally, the dataset ends in April 2026, and extending the time frame would allow validation of long-term stabilisation trends.
Conclusion
This analysis confirms that the S&P 500 has delivered positive average monthly returns over 2020–2026, with volatility concentrated in periods of macroeconomic stress (2020 COVID-19, 2022 rate hikes). For retail investors, the results reinforce the value of long-term investing and volatility monitoring as tools to manage market risk. The Python-based workflow used in this project demonstrates how accessible data analysis tools can empower retail investors to make informed decisions based on empirical market data.
